###  1m – 1M – 2NT   \ref{1m1M2NT}

Opener's jump to 2N shows one of two different hand types:
- 16+, fit
- 16+, 6m and 0-2 in responder's major
With the latter type, opener promises some kind of stoppers in both the unbid suits.
If not, he has other bids to choose among.

Example:
\bdn {
1♦ 1♠
2N ?
}

\bids {
3♣ | (Other minor) GF, relay
3♦ | NF, weak (all other rebids are GF)
3♥ | GF, NAT, 5-5
3♠ | GF, 6+♠
3N | to play opposite the long minor
4♦ | ST
}

\bdn {
1♦ 1♠
2N 3♣
?
}

\bids {
3♠ | 16-17 with support
3♦/♥ | 6-card minor, interest of slam
3N | 6-card minor, normal bid
4X | 18-19 with support, new suit is splinter
}

With the one-suited hand opener can bid anything at the 3-level, except for the bid major.
3N is NF while suit bids are forcing.

As a general rule, with support opener bids 3M with 16-17 HCP and bids at the 4-level with 18-19 HCP.
A bid in a new suit then shows a singleton.

