\arg{Rodwell: Basic responses to a Mini Multi}{
If responder would want to stop in two of opener’s major,
he bids a ‘pass or correct’ 2\h.

A 2\h response is appropriate on a hand that likes neither major, or likes only spades.
After all, if opener has spades he will correct and you can reconsider what to do then. Example:
\hand{K865.2.AK876.K83}{Responder}
If partner has a weak two in hearts, you want to play 2\h.
If partner has a weak two in spades you want to be in 4\s.
The solution is to bid 2\h, pass or correct, playing there if partner has hearts.
If opener corrects to 2\s, you jump to 4\s.

What if you have a hand that likes hearts but not spades? Now you can bid 2\s,
which is also a pass or correct response. An obvious example would be the previous
hand with the majors switched. You bid 2\s, playing there if opener has spades
and when he corrects (if he should have hearts), you would bid 4\h.

It is not necessary to have game ambitions for a pass or correct response:
\hand{J87.76.A7654.K87}{Responder}
You would respond 2\h, pass or correct. If opener bids 2\s, you would raise
to 3\s, just as if partner opened a weak 2\s. Think of these types of follow-up
sequences this way:
*once partner shows a specific weak two, bid what you would have bid had he opened a weak two in that suit*.
There are a few twists on this idea I will get into later.
On this hand, you would raise 2\s to 3\s, preemptive. As usual, when partner
opens a weak two you need to bid 2NT to show game interest.

If responder wants to preemptively raise either major, he responds 3\h, pass or correct:
\hand{J87.Q76.83.AJ765}{Responder}
Respond 3\h to 2\d, pass or correct, but preemptive.

If responder wants to be in game opposite either weak two he can respond 4\h,
pass or correct. This might be preemptive or could be a better hand,
just as over a natural weak two.
}

Заявка масти после коррекции - NAT, NF: 2♦-2♥ - 2♠-3♣/♦ – контракт.

\arg{Rodwell: hand that wants to be in 3♣}{
\hand{2.KQ8.A6.KJT9765}{Responder}
If partner has a weak two in spades, it rates to be right to play in 3\c.
If partner has hearts, you want to bid 4\h.
This is a drawback of Mini Multi’s ambiguity about the major.

With a hand that (probably) wants to be in 3\c, we respond the LONGER major, in this case 2\h.
If opener passes you are in a playable contract (and they might be able to make 4\s anyway).
In the more likely case that he corrects to 2\s, you then bid 3\c which is to play.

If responder bids 2\s over 2\d, I recommend these modified rebids: 2NT and 3\c.
This way, responder can still get to 3\c (imagine the last responder hand with the majors reversed).
More importantly, responder can get to 3\h or 4\h from his side,
using the range information to make a decision about how much to bid.
}

Most of the time if responder has a long major he will not want to force to game.
The solution is to bid your long major, pass or correct, then when corrected,
rebid your major. This is non-forcing but opener might raise with a suitable hand.

\arg{Rodwell: 3♣ response as a forcing hand with own long major}{
Opener bids 3\d and responder bids his long major. If opener wants to raise
that major, he bids 4 of the major; with a good raise he can bid 4\c or 4\d
(4\c is a cuebid, 4\d denies a club control and might have all values in the majors):
\deal{W:K87.AJT876.876.2 E:AQ96543.2.AK2.AK}
\bdn {
2\d 3\c\1{game forcing with a long major}
3\d 3\s\2{spades is the long major}
4\c\3{cuebid, good raise} 4NT
5\h 7\s
}

If responder bids 3\h and opener doesn’t want to raise, he can bid 3NT
with something in the minors. Most of the time he won’t have that so he
can just wait by bidding 3\s (which is obviously his major) and let responder
do what he wishes (natural continuations).

If responder bids 3\s and opener doesn’t want to bid 3NT, he is stuck.
I would say that opener can bid 3NT with something in only one minor and whether
to leave it there is up to responder. One other tool will help:
*responder’s 3NT continuation (instead of 3\s) shows long spades but willingness to play 3NT*.
\deal{W:2.KJT764.876.JT6 E:AQT876.2.AKJ.AQ3}
\bdn {
2\d 3\c
3\d 3NT
}
Not that 3NT will always make but responder can hardly fail to force to game.
}

